  "prompt": "How do I report identity theft?",
  "response": "Okay, dealing with identity theft is stressful, but taking the right steps quickly can minimize the damage. Here's a breakdown of how to report it, broken down into actionable steps:\n\n**1. Immediate Actions (Within 24-48 Hours):**\n\n*   **Contact the Businesses Where the Fraud Occurred:**\n    *   Call the fraud departments of any banks, credit card companies, retailers, or other businesses where you know your information was used fraudulently.\n    *   Close or freeze accounts that have been compromised.\n    *   Change passwords and PINs on all your accounts (especially email, banking, and social media).  Use strong, unique passwords for each.\n    *   Keep records of all conversations, including dates, times, names of representatives, and what was discussed.\n\n*   **Place a Fraud Alert on Your Credit Reports:**\n    *   Contact **one** of the three major credit bureaus:\n        *   **Equifax:** 1-800-525-6285 (www.equifax.com)\n        *   **Experian:** 1-888-397-3742 (www.experian.com)\n        *   **TransUnion:** 1-800-680-7289 (www.transunion.com)\n    *   When you place a fraud alert with one bureau, they are required to notify the other two.\n    *   **Types of Fraud Alerts:**\n        *   **Initial Fraud Alert (1 year):** This is the standard alert and requires businesses to take reasonable steps to verify your identity before granting credit.\n        *   **Extended Fraud Alert (7 years):**  Requires you to file an identity theft report with law enforcement (see below).  Provides greater protection.\n        *   **Active Duty Military Alert (1 year):** For those in the military.\n\n*   **Order Copies of Your Credit Reports:**\n    *   You are entitled to a free credit report from each of the three major credit bureaus every 12 months through www.annualcreditreport.com.  Order them now to review for fraudulent activity.\n    *   Carefully examine each report for unauthorized accounts, inquiries, or incorrect personal information.\n\n**2. File an Official Identity Theft Report:**\n\n*   **File a Report with the Federal Trade Commission (FTC):**\n    *   Go to IdentityTheft.gov: This is the official FTC website for reporting identity theft.\n    *   Follow the instructions to create an IdentityTheft.gov report.  This report is important because it:\n        *   Helps you create an Identity Theft Report, which you'll need for many steps.\n        *   Provides guidance on what steps to take based on the type of identity theft you experienced.\n        *   Can be used to support your claims with creditors and other businesses.\n    *   You can also call the FTC Identity Theft Hotline at 1-877-ID-THEFT (1-877-438-4338).\n\n*   **File a Police Report:**\n    *   Contact your local police department or law enforcement agency.  Even if they can't directly investigate, having a police report is crucial for:\n        *   Supporting your claims with creditors, banks, and other institutions.\n        *   Obtaining an Extended Fraud Alert on your credit reports.\n        *   Potentially helping with prosecution if the identity thief is caught.\n    *   Bring copies of your FTC Identity Theft Report, credit reports, and any other evidence of the identity theft to the police.\n    *   Be persistent; some police departments may be reluctant to take a report for identity theft, but it's your right to file one.  Explain why you need it.\n\n**3. Ongoing Monitoring and Recovery:**\n\n*   **Review Your Credit Reports Regularly:** Continue to monitor your credit reports from all three bureaus for any new unauthorized activity.  Consider using a credit monitoring service (some are free, others charge a fee) to receive alerts about changes to your credit files.\n*   **Keep Detailed Records:** Maintain a file with copies of all reports, letters, emails, and other communications related to the identity theft.  This will be essential for resolving disputes.\n*   **Dispute Fraudulent Information:**\n    *   Write to each credit bureau to dispute any inaccurate or fraudulent information on your credit report.\n    *   Include copies of your FTC Identity Theft Report, police report (if you have one), and any other supporting documentation.\n    *   The credit bureaus have 30 days to investigate your dispute.\n*   **Consider a Credit Freeze (Security Freeze):**\n    *   A credit freeze restricts access to your credit report, making it more difficult for identity thieves to open new accounts in your name.\n    *   You must contact each credit bureau separately to place a freeze.\n    *   You can temporarily lift the freeze when you need to apply for credit.\n    *   Credit freezes are now free in all states.\n\n**Important Considerations and Tips:**\n\n*   **Act Quickly:** The sooner you report the identity theft, the less damage the thief can do.\n*   **Be Persistent:** Resolving identity theft issues can be a long and frustrating process.  Don't give up.\n*   **Keep Copies:** Always keep copies of everything you send and receive related to the identity theft.\n*   **Be Aware of Scams:** Identity thieves may try to contact you pretending to be from banks, credit bureaus, or government agencies.  Never give out personal information over the phone or online unless you initiated the contact and are sure you're dealing with a legitimate organization.\n*   **Review Bank and Credit Card Statements Carefully:** Check your statements every month for any unauthorized transactions.\n*   **Protect Your Personal Information:** Be careful about sharing your Social Security number, bank account numbers, and other sensitive information.  Shred documents containing personal information before discarding them.\n*   **If Your Social Security Number is Compromised:** The Social Security Administration (SSA) has specific guidance. Contact them immediately.\n*   **Legal Assistance:** If the identity theft is complex or causing significant financial hardship, consider consulting with an attorney specializing in identity theft or consumer law.\n\n**Where to Get More Help:**\n\n*   **Federal Trade Commission (FTC):** IdentityTheft.gov (official website)\n*   **Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB):** www.consumerfinance.gov\n*   **Identity Theft Resource Center (ITRC):** www.idtheftcenter.org (non-profit organization)\n*   **Your State Attorney General's Office:** Provides consumer protection resources.\n\nBy taking these steps, you can help protect yourself from further damage and begin the process of recovering from identity theft. Good luck!\n",
